Labor mobility



1. Background


A major economic objective of public goods, provided by a government, is the job creation that would provide income to its citizen. When this does not work, or work less than somewhere else, regional income disparity arises.


2. Labor mobility (migration)


  • rural areas to cities (in the same country).

    • Percent of urban population (WDI)

    • Internal Migration in Japan (Statistics Bureau of Japan)


  • poorer to richer countries

    • Net migration stock (WDI)

    • Remittance Matrix (https://www.worldbank.org/en/topic/migrationremittancesdiasporaissues/brief/migration-remittances-data)


  • the opposite does happen though in smaller scale


3. The push and pull factors


  • poverty and wealth


  • distance

    • physical distance

    • culture

    • colonial past

    • Legal framework


4. Challenges


  • mitigation of the impacts at destination and source regions/countries

    • economic impacts

    • social impacts


  • mobile workers’ rights

    • same job same work (equal pay for equal work)

    • others


  • will migration workers really need to migrate if remote-work become a norm? Would the impacts be disastrous for skill workers in higher income countries?
